<br>
1.  Do NOT give the Harness of control to the broodmother unless she is stationary in her cave.  If she is moving at all, petition immediately and a GM may be able to reset her.  I haven't been successful with this, but the Guides and GM are well aware of the bug and don't make you wait too long before giving it a shot.<br>
<br>
2.  If you get aggro'd in the cave (and you probably will), immediately run toward Thurg.  Do not stop, do not pass go and get your 200pp.  Run up to the little guard hut.  That will outrun the aggro of whoever has become pissed at you.  At that point, you can track across to the broodmother and follow her to the fort without an angry shardwurm on your tail.<br>
<br>
3.  As mentioned, let the broodmother attack the other named giant.  You will see two giants despawn and respawn.  When I did it, Fergul went from blue to yellow (I think I was 42 or 43).  Anyway, Fergul will take off toward the zone.  Let him clear the fort and then snare the bejeezus out of him.  If you let him get too close to the zone (and I mean even near where it dips down to the zone line) he will despawn and leave you extremely pissed.  Again, this happened to me the first time I did it.<br>
<br>
4.  Unless some of the lvl 50+ folk are able to help out, I strongly suggest aggro-kiting him.  He has a ton more HP's than regular giants and hits pretty dang hard.  Get snare on him and have the caster keep aggro and back track while you beat on his backside.  Be careful of wandering wolves and FG's.  You're a ranger, control the crowd with roots while Fergul is being kited.<br>
<br>
It's really not too hard, but its very satisfying.  I know me and Ratimus have double teamed him before at 43 and 45 before, but it's better to have a third, and a 4th, heck a full group is nice too :P  Just make sure to avoid the bugs and snare before despawn and you'll have some fancy new pants soon enough.  Give me a yell if I'm on, I'm always willing to help out with it. <p>- Eriul - 
